    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"living constitution\" argument is precisely that its proponents reject the idea of a fixed, original meaning, believing the document must adapt to contemporary society. Critics often view this as judicial activism because it grants judges the power to mold fundamental law based on present-day political consensus. If judges routinely reshape the Constitution through evolving norms, the rule of law shifts from adherence to fixed text to deference to judicial philosophy. This makes the concept of an unchanging constitutional standard significantly weaker.",
      "source": "target",
